		<header>
			
			<h1>Sugar surpluses expected to exert downward pressure on prices, but uncertainties remain </h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 October 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A report from Rabobank in September 2012 has underlined the high levels of price volatility on global sugar markets, with prices increasing by 20% between mid June and the end of July 2012, before losing all the price gains on news of better than expected harvests in Brazil, India, Russia, China and Thailand. This has seen ‘an increase in global sugar production of some 8% from 2010/11 to 2011/12’ and an increase in global stocks and the stocks-to-use ratio. For its part, ISO is projecting a global sugar production for 2012–13 of ‘a record 177.4 million tonnes’, an increase of 2.3%. With consumption rising more slowly, this is projected by ISO to leave an output surplus of 5.9 million tonnes. By the end of the 2012/13 season, the ISO is projecting a stocks-to-use ratio of ‘around 40%’. This signals an end to ‘the period of low stocks’ which characterised the global sugar market from 2008/09 to 2011/12. This is expected to exert a downward pressure on prices.</p><p>At the same time, the sugar research and brokerage house Kingsman reported ‘a lack of demand amid a global surplus’. According to reports from Bloomberg, Kingsman have commented that ‘sellers will struggle to get buyers for raw sugar in the season starting October’, with prices remaining ‘under pressure in the next six to 12 months on excessive supplies.’ Furthermore, ‘supplies will exceed demand by 8.7 million tonnes in the 2012-13 season (production 180 million tonnes, consumption 171.3 million tonnes), which will add to the ‘surplus of 10.1 million tonnes in the current season’. As a result, ‘sugar will have to be stored on lack of demand.’</p><p>On 20 September, Czarnikow added their voice to warnings on global sugar prices, despite concerns over the Indian harvest. They warned that although prices had fallen ‘near 2-year lows’ (nearly 50% below a 30-year peak reached in February 2011), they ‘may need to decline further to encourage demand’. These forecasts followed earlier statements from Standard Chartered Bank that sugar prices were poised for a recovery. Standard Chartered maintained that ‘investors were underestimating production risks’, with uncertainties remaining over output in China, India and Thailand. They took the view that the New York raw sugar price will average 22c/lb in 2012 and 25c/lb in 2013. Commerzbank, however, takes the view that the current supply surplus ‘greatly limits [upward] potential for sugar prices’.</p><p>Sugar prices towards the end of September increased slightly as a result of a ‘stalled’ recovery in the Brazilian sugar harvest, following mill closures for maintenance, a mid-season development perhaps in part linked to the perilous financial state of many Brazilian sugar mills.</p>
		
		
