				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>With the price guarantees for ACP sugar abolished from 1 October 2012, the return to sugar surpluses and consequent downward pressures on global sugar prices do not look positive for producers regarding future prices on the EU market. In the new era of market-determined prices in the EU and considerable volatility in global sugar prices, it is clear that contractual negotiations will be the critical determinant of the prices secured by ACP sugar exporters.</p><p>This does not mean that EU policy measures will not play a role. The EU sugar import regime continues to be highly regulated. How the EC chooses to manage the deployment of current EU sugar market policy tools (notably the establishment and allocation of tariff-rate quotas and regulations on the use of out-of-quota sugar) will have an important bearing on the supply and demand situation on different components of the EU sugar market, and hence on price trends in the coming three seasons (i.e. before any new agreed sugar sector reforms enter into effect).</p><p>The management of the current sugar regime is only in part linked to the debate on the future of the EU sugar regime, since any agreed CAP reforms would only begin to take effect in the 2015/16 sugar season at the earliest. While both traditional EU sugar refiners and EU sugar users are pushing for a more liberal and transparent sugar import regime, in order to generate fair competition on European sugar markets, European sugar beet farmers and CEFS, the European Committee of Sugar Manufacturers, are seeking a maintenance of both import restrictions and production quotas until 2020, to allow the European sugar sector to effectively complete the ongoing restructuring process.</p><p>In the interim, how the EC manages the current regime will be critical to sugar market price formation within the EU.</p>
		</div>
		
